const Q_GOVERNMENT_1999=[{"id": "objective>Government>1999>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal state, power is shared</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">between the central government and the local authorities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">among the major regions of federation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">among the major regions of the country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">between the central government and other co-ordinate units</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal state, power is shared between the central government and other co-ordinate units. This is the basic principle of federalism where power is divided between a central authority and constituent political units. The central government handles issues that affect the entire federation, while the co-ordinate units (states, provinces, etc.) handle local issues.</div>", "topic": "STRUCTURES OF GOVERNANCE : FEDERAL FEATURES, REASONS FOR ADOPTION, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal system of government, the central is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">superior to the other components</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inferior to the other components</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">equal to the other cmponents</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of unlimited jurisdiction</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Federal system advocates a stronger central government</div>", "topic": "STRUCTURES OF GOVERNANCE : FEDERAL FEATURES, REASONS FOR ADOPTION, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a presidential system of government, ministers are</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individually views cannot be expressed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">decisions taken are defended in spite of individual opinions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">government cannot be personalized</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">those who hold different views must acquiesce</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principle of collective responsibility. The question is self explanatory in relation to the answer.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : OLIGARCHY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A government controlled by a few people for their own interests is said to be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an autocracy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a tyranny</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an oligarchy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a meritocracy</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oligarchy is a conceptual form of power structure in which power rests with a small number of people.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : OLIGARCHY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the parliamentary system of government, formal legislation can take the following forms except</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">royal proclamations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">order in council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acts of parliament</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ministerial pronouncement</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a parliamentary system of government, formal legislation can take the form of royal proclamations, orders in council, and acts of parliament. However, ministerial pronouncements are not considered formal legislation. They are statements or announcements made by ministers, which may outline policy or intentions, but they do not have the force of law like the other forms of legislation listed.</div>", "topic": "SYSTEMS OF GOVERNANCE : PARLIAMENTARY SYSTEM OF GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the distinctive features of democracy is that it</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">connotes civil rule</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">facilitates popular participation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provides for a unicameral legislature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is not associated with one - part system</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the distinctive features of democracy is that it facilitates popular participation. This means that in a democratic system, citizens have the right and are encouraged to participate in the decision-making process, either directly or through elected representatives. This can be through voting in elections, participating in public debates, or through other forms of civic engagement. The other options do not accurately represent distinctive features of democracy. While democracy does connote civil rule, it is not exclusive to democracy. Similarly, not all democracies provide for a unicameral legislature, and democracy is not associated with a one-party system, but rather, it encourages multi-party competition.</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : DEMOCRACY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A hereditary system of government is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an oligarchy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a gerontocracy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an aristocracy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a monarchy</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A hereditary system of government is a monarchy. In a monarchy, the position of the head of state is passed down through family lines. This is different from an oligarchy (rule by a small group), a gerontocracy (rule by the elderly), and an aristocracy (rule by a privileged class).</div>", "topic": "FORMS OF GOVERNMENT : MONARCHY FEATURES, MERITS AND DEMERITS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The separation of judicial, legislative and executive functions is designed to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promote freedom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prevent tyranny</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promote peace</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prevent anarchy</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The separation of judicial, legislative and executive functions is designed to prevent tyranny. This principle, known as the separation of powers, is a model for the governance of a state. Under this model, the state is divided into branches, each with separate and independent powers and areas of responsibility so that the powers of one branch are not in conflict with the powers associated with the other branches. The typical division is into three branches: a legislature, an executive, and a judiciary, which is the model for a majority of democracies.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : LEGISLATURE TYPES, STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bicameral legislature are a common feature of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monarchical systems</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">confederal systems</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">federal systems</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unitary systems</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bicameral legislature is a common feature of federal systems. A bicameral legislature is a legislative system with two chambers, an upper and lower house. In a federal system, this allows for equal representation of the states at the federal level (in the upper house) and representation based on population in the lower house.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : LEGISLATURE TYPES, STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal constitution, legislative powers that are shared by two levels of government are referred to as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exclusive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">extra ordinary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">residual</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concurrent</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a federal constitution, legislative powers that are shared by two levels of government are referred to as concurrent powers. Concurrent powers are powers that are shared by both the state and the federal government. These powers may be exercised simultaneously within the same territory and in relation to the same body of citizens. They are contrasted with exclusive powers (powers that only the federal government has) and residual powers (powers not listed in the constitution, so they are left up to individual states to exercise).</div>", "topic": "THE STRUCTURE AND WORKINGS OF NIGERIAN FEDERALISM : RATIONALE FOR A FEDERAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most important function of the executive organ of government is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">formulate policies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">give assent to bills</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">control foreign policy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enforce laws</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The executive branch of government is primarily responsible for enforcing laws. This is the most important function of the executive organ of government. The executive branch includes the President, the Vice President, and other executive officers to enforce laws and maintain peace and order. The other options such as formulating policies, giving assent to bills, and controlling foreign policy are also functions of the executive branch, but enforcing laws is the most important.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : EXECUTIVE-TYPES, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The process of learning the norms and values associated with a political system is referred to as political</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">socialization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indoctrination</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">culture</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">participation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Political socialization is the process by which individuals learn and frequently internalize a political lens framing their perceptions of how power is arranged and how the world around them is (and should be) organized. Those perceptions, in turn, shape and define individuals' definitions of who they are and how they should behave in the political and economic institutions in which they live.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : POLITICAL PROCESSES: POLITICAL SOCIALIZATION, POLITICAL PARTICIPATION AND POLITICAL CULTURE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following best describes the role of the civil service?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promoting the interest of civil servants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">advising government and implementig its policies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keeping records for government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">providing information on government and its agencies</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The civil service is a sector of government composed mainly of career bureaucrats hired on professional merit rather than appointed or elected. Their primary role is to advise the government and implement its policies. They are employed to implement the decisions of elected officials, which they do by creating the rules and regulations that dictate how specific government services are to be carried out.</div>", "topic": "INSTITUTIONS OF GOVERNMENT IN THE POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : THE EXECUTIVE – STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND WORKINGS."}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One instrument for safeguarding the rights of citizens is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">judicial interpretation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">presidential pardon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">legislative intervention</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">writ of habeas corpus</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A writ of habeas corpus is used to bring a prisoner or other detainee (e.g. institutionalized mental patient) before the court to determine if the person's imprisonment or detention is lawful. A habeas petition proceeds as a civil action against the State agent (usually a warden) who holds the defendant in custody.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : JUDICIARY FUNCTIONS, POWERS AND COMPONENTS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Legislative control over delegated legislation can be performed through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">withdrawal of delegated powers by the judiciary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nullification of unconstitutional legislation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">investigation into the exercise of delegated power</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">approval of legislation by the Chief justice</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Legislative control over delegated legislation can be performed through investigation into the exercise of delegated power. Delegated legislation refers to laws made by an individual or body under powers given to them by an Act of Parliament. The legislature can control this by investigating how these powers are used.</div>", "topic": "PROCESSES OF LEGISLATION : DELEGATED LEGISLATION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The feature which best differentiates pressure groups from political parties is that they do not</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have interest in politics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seek to influence public opinion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have permananent organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nominate ministers</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The feature which best differentiates pressure groups from political parties is that they do not nominate ministers. Pressure groups are organizations that try to influence public policy or legislation, but unlike political parties, they do not nominate candidates for election.</div>", "topic": "PRESSURE GROUPS : DIFFERENCES BETWEEN PRESSURE GROUPS AND POLITICAL PARTIES."}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The notion of equality before the law is the same as the principle of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">supremacy of the constitution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rule of law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">independence of the judiciary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social equality</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The notion of equality before the law is the same as the principle of rule of law. The rule of law is a legal principle that law should govern a nation, and that all are subject to it, including those who govern. It implies that every citizen is subject to the law, including people who are lawmakers, law enforcement officials, and judges. In this sense, it stands for the supremacy of law over the supremacy of individual will.</div>", "topic": "BASIC CONCEPTS OF GOVERNMENT : POWER, AUTHORITY, LEGITIMACY AND SOVEREIGNTY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A constitution is classified as unwritten when it</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">does not emanate from the legislature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provides for separation of powers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">originates from Britain</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is not contained in any single document</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A constitution is classified as unwritten when it is not contained in any single document. An unwritten constitution is a type of constitution where the fundamental rules often take the form of customs, usage, precedent and a variety of statutes and legal instruments. An example is the constitution of the United Kingdom. It is not contained in a single, codified document but in a variety of documents, statutes, court judgments and treaties.</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTION : TYPES OF CONSTITUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A state is said to be fascist when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its leader is partriotic but the citizens are not</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all rights and liberties are subordinated to state interest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its citizens are fanatically in love with their leader</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all fights and liberties are placed above state interests</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fascism is a system of government led by a dictator who typically rules by forcefully and often violently suppressing opposition and criticism, controlling all industry and commerce, and promoting nationalism and often racism.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL IDEOLOGIES : FASCISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A dominant two -party system is operated in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the United kingdom and United States</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">India and Pakistan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">France and Germany</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">South African and Senegal</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A dominant two-party system is a political system where two major political parties dominate the government. One of the two parties typically holds a majority in the legislature and is usually referred to as the majority party while the other is the minority party. This system is operated in the United Kingdom (Conservative Party and Labour Party) and the United States (Democratic Party and Republican Party). Therefore, the correct answer is 'the United Kingdom and United States'.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY SYSTEMS : PARTY SYSTEMS – DEFINITION, ORGANIZATION, FUNCTIONS."}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Indirect legislation can be achieved by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">judicial interpretation and precedent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">passing of bills and making of decrees</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">passing a private member's bill</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the two legislative chambers considering a bill</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Indirect legislation can be achieved by judicial interpretation and precedent. This is because the judiciary, in interpreting the law, can set precedents that effectively create new laws or modify existing ones. This is a form of indirect legislation because it does not involve the formal legislative process of passing bills in a legislative body.</div>", "topic": "PROCESSES OF LEGISLATION"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naturalization is a process of acquiring citizenship by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persons of dual nationality</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">foreign visitors to a country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resident foreigners of good character</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persons born abroad</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naturalization is a process by which a non-citizen in a country may acquire citizenship or nationality of that country. It may be done by a statute, without any effort on the part of the individual, or it may involve an application and approval by legal authorities. The rules of naturalization vary from country to country but typically include a promise to obey and uphold that country's laws, taking and passing a citizenship or civics test, and may require that the applicant has had a permanent residence in the country for a certain number of years.</div>", "topic": "CITIZENSHIP"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ideology which stats that each person is the best judge of what is in his self interest is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">liberalism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">socialism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fascism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">feudalism</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Liberalism is a political and moral philosophy based on the rights of the individual, liberty, consent of the governed, political equality and equality before the law. </div>", "topic": "POLITICAL IDEOLOGIES : LIBERALISM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Code of Conduct Bureau was established essentially to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ensure the independence of the public service</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enhance probity and accountability in public service</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protect the rights of public servants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reduce corruption in public life</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Code of Conduct Bureau was established essentially to enhance probity and accountability in public service. The Bureau is mandated to establish and maintain a high standard of morality in the conduct of government business and to ensure that the actions and behavior of public officers conform to the highest standards of public morality and accountability.</div>", "topic": "GOVERNMENT : PUBLIC SERVICE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The British Government revoked the Charter of the Royal Niger Company and took over the ministration of Nigeria in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1861</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1885</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1900</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1914</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The British Government revoked the Charter of the Royal Niger Company and took over the administration of Nigeria in 1900. The Royal Niger Company's charter was revoked because the British government felt that the company was not capable of managing the vast Nigerian territory. The British government then established the Protectorate of Northern Nigeria and the Protectorate of Southern Nigeria, effectively taking over the administration of the country.</div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : THE BRITISH PROCESS OF ACQUISITION – TRADE, MISSIONARY ACTIVITIES, COMPANY RULE, CROWN COLONY, PROTECTORATE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The independence Constitution can be described as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monarchical and presidential</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Republican and parliamentary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monarchical and parliamentary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">federal and republican</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The independence Constitution of Nigeria can be described as monarchical and parliamentary. This is because, at the time of independence in 1960, Nigeria adopted the Westminster system of government, which is a parliamentary system. The Queen of England was the head of state (hence monarchical), represented in Nigeria by a Governor-General, while the Prime Minister was the head of government. The system was parliamentary because the Prime Minister was a member of the parliament and was appointed by the Governor-General from the party with the majority in the parliament.</div>", "topic": "POST - INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTIONS : 1963 CONSTITUTION CHARACTERISTICS AND SHORTCOMINGS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first Head of Government in independent Nigeria was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nnamdi Azikiwe</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahmadu Bello</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tafawa Balewa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Herbert Macaulay</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The first Head of Government in independent Nigeria was Tafawa Balewa. He served as the Prime Minister of Nigeria from 1960 to 1966. Nnamdi Azikiwe was the first President, Ahmadu Bello was the Premier of Northern Nigeria, and Herbert Macaulay was a Nigerian nationalist who played a key role in Nigeria's struggle for independence.</div>", "topic": "ARMS OF GOVERNMENT : EXECUTIVE-TYPES, FUNCTIONS AND POWERS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following parties formed the opposition in the House of Representatives during Nigeria's First Republic?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">AG and UMBC</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NCNC and NEPU</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NPC and NNDP</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">NCNC and AG</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During Nigeria's First Republic, the Action Group (AG) and the United Middle Belt Congress (UMBC) formed the opposition in the House of Representatives. The National Council of Nigeria and the Cameroons (NCNC), the Northern People's Congress (NPC), and the Nigerian National Democratic Party (NNDP) were part of the ruling coalition.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : FIRST REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A feature common to the 1963, 1979 and 1989 constitutions of Nigeria was that they provided for a</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">republican system</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prime minister</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ceremonial head of state</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> president has head of government</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 1963, 1979, and 1989 constitutions of Nigeria all provided for a republican system of government. A republican system of government is a type of government in which the country is considered a 'public matter' with the country's head of state being an appointed or elected individual, and not a monarch.</div>", "topic": "POST - INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTIONS : 1963 CONSTITUTION CHARACTERISTICS AND SHORTCOMINGS~~POST - INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTIONS : 1979 CONSTITUTION CHARACTERISTICS AND SHORTCOMINGS~~POST - INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTIONS : 1989 CONSTITUTION CHARACTERISTICS AND SHORTCOMINGS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Lagos Colony and Protectorate was amalgamated with The Protectorate of Southern Nigeria in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1886</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1893</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1906</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1922</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Lagos Colony and Protectorate was amalgamated with The Protectorate of Southern Nigeria in 1906. This was part of the series of changes in administrative structures instituted by the British colonial authorities.</div>", "topic": "IMPERIALIST PENETRATION : THE BRITISH PROCESS OF ACQUISITION – TRADE, MISSIONARY ACTIVITIES, COMPANY RULE, CROWN COLONY, PROTECTORATE"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the 1957 constitutional conference the Willink Commission was set up to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recommend a date for independence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suggest an equitable revenue allocation formula</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">create new regions in Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recommend solutions to the problem of the minorities</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Willink Commission was set up during the 1957 constitutional conference to recommend solutions to the problem of the minorities. The commission was named after its chairman, Sir Henry Willink, and it was tasked with addressing the fears of ethnic minorities about possible domination by the majority ethnic groups after independence.</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTIONAL DEVELOPMENT IN NIGERIA : INDEPENDENCE CONSTITUTION 1960"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The duty of an Alkali under the Hausa Fularti political system is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adjudicate under Islamic laws</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make Islamic laws</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">execute Islamic laws</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make treaties under Islamic laws</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Hausa Fulani political system, the duty of an Alkali is to adjudicate under Islamic laws. An Alkali is a judge who makes decisions based on the principles of Sharia (Islamic law). They do not make or execute the laws, but interpret and apply them in cases brought before them.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : HAUSA PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The motion for self-government in Niger was proposed by Chief Anthony Enahoro in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1950</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1953</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1956</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1958</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1953, Enahoro became the first to move the motion for Nigeria's independence? which was eventually granted in 1960, after several political setbacks and defeats in the parliament. Enahoro has been regarded by academics and many Nigerians, as the \"Father of Nigeria State\".</div>", "topic": "CONSTITUTIONAL DEVELOPMENT IN NIGERIA : JOHN MACPHERSON CONSTITUTION 1951"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The legislative functions of the government of Benin Kingdom were performed by the Oba and a council of Chiefs known as the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Esama</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ndichie</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Uzama</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Enigie</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Benin Kingdom, the legislative functions were performed by the Oba and a council of Chiefs known as the Uzama. The Uzama were the kingmakers and they played a significant role in the governance of the kingdom. They were involved in making laws and decisions for the kingdom.</div>", "topic": "PRE-COLONIAL POLITICS : IGBO PRE-COLONIAL SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The highest ruling body under the Murtala'' Obasanjo regime differed remarkably from that of the Gowon administration because of the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inclusion of civilians as members</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exclusion of military governors from the council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inclusion of of the Chief Justice as a member</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exclusion of the Inspector General of Police from the council</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The highest ruling body under the Murtala/Obasanjo regime differed remarkably from that of the Gowon administration because of the inclusion of civilians as members. This was a significant shift from the military-dominated council of the Gowon era, marking a transition towards civilian rule.</div>", "topic": "INSTITUTIONS OF GOVERNMENT IN THE POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : THE EXECUTIVE – STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS AND WORKINGS."}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Decree No, 34 of May 1966 is also known as the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">State Security Decree</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Suspension and Modification Decree</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Public Order Decree</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Unification Decree</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> It was the decree that transferred all the autonomous powers of the four regions then to the centre. The regions then were Northern Region, Eastern Region, Western Region and Mid-Western Region. <br/> </div>", "topic": "PROCESSES OF LEGISLATION : DECREES"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1979, the Unity Party of Nigeria contested and won. gubernatorial elections in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lagos Kwara, Oyo, Ogun and Bendel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lagos , Ogun, Imo, Oyo and Bendel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lagos, Kwara, Ogun,Oyo ,Ondo Bendel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lagos, Kwara, Ogun, Oyo and Ondo</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Unity Party of Nigeria (UPN) in 1979 contested and won gubernatorial elections in Lagos, Ogun, Oyo, Ondo, and Bendel. This is a historical fact and can be verified from various sources.</div>", "topic": "POLITICAL PARTIES AND PARTY POLITICS IN POST-INDEPENDENCE NIGERIA : FOURTH REPUBLIC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rate are usually collected in Nigeria by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ministries of Commerce in the states</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The department councils</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The traditional rules</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The department of inland revenue</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rates in Nigeria are usually collected by the local government councils. This is because the Nigerian constitution empowers the local government councils to collect rates such as tenement rates and market taxes.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL GOVERNMENT :FEATURES OF LOCAL GOVERNMENT REFORMS 1976, 1989 - STRUCTURE, FUNCTIONS, FINANCE AND INTER-GOVERNMENTAL RELATIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the main reasons for the creation of more local government in Nigeria is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make them more responsive to people's needs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weaken the powers of traditional authorities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make them more receptive to traditional rulers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">establish them as the third tier in the federal structure</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The creation of more local governments in Nigeria is primarily to make them more responsive to people's needs. Local governments are created to bring governance closer to the people, thereby making it more responsive to their needs. This is because local governments are closer to the people and understand their needs better than the central government.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL GOVERNMENT"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Based on its objectives, the Organization of African Unity can primarily be classified as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a social organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a political organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a cultural organization</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an economic organization</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Organization of African Unity (OAU), now the African Union (AU), is primarily a political organization. Its main objectives include promoting unity and solidarity among African states, defending their sovereignty, and coordinating and intensifying their cooperation and efforts to achieve a better life for the peoples of Africa. These objectives are primarily political in nature.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's role in ECOMOG is essentially informed by her</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">desire for peace and stability</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chairmanship of ECOWAS</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">desire to establish democracy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">membership of ECOWAS</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's role in ECOMOG (Economic Community of West African States Monitoring Group) is primarily informed by her desire for peace and stability in the West African region. ECOMOG was established as a peacekeeping force to intervene in member states during civil wars and conflicts. Nigeria, being the largest economy and most populous country in West Africa, has a vested interest in the peace and stability of the region.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : ECOWAS"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The annual budget of the OAU is approved by the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Council of Ministers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Secretary General</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Assembly of Heads of State and Governement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">General Assembly</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The annual budget of the OAU (Organization of African Unity, now African Union) is approved by the Assembly of Heads of State and Government. The Assembly is the supreme decision-making organ of the Union and is composed of Heads of State and Government or their duly accredited representatives. The Assembly meets once a year and makes decisions on policies, goals, and budgets of the Union.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : OAU/AU"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The major strategy used by OPEC to influence oil price is by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">allocating production quotas to members</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> influencing buyers at the international market to buy at high prices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">allowing member countries to produce at their discretion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increasing the supply of the commodity</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) is a group consisting of 14 of the world's major oil-exporting nations. OPEC's most effective method for managing oil prices is by setting production quotas for its member nations. This is done to prevent market gluts and to keep prices stable.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : OPEC"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth because of her</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tacit approval of military dictatorship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">negative position towards other nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">complete negligence of freedom of the press</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">violation of fundamental human rights</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth in 1995 due to the execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni activists, which was seen as a gross violation of fundamental human rights. The Commonwealth is a political association of 54 member states, nearly all of which are former territories of the British Empire. The chief institutions of the organisation are the Commonwealth Secretariat, which focuses on intergovernmental aspects, and the Commonwealth Foundation, which focuses on non-governmental relations amongst member states.</div>", "topic": "NIGERIA IN INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : THE COMMONWEALTH"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's non-aligned policy means that she</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not take sides in international issues based on idealogical considerations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have nothing to do with the super powers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">avoid having any dealing with any country with ideological leanings</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">relate only with member countries of the non - aligned movement</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nigeria's non-aligned policy means that she does not take sides in international issues based on ideological considerations. The Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) is a group of states which are not formally aligned with or against any major power bloc. They are the countries of the \"Third World\" that do not choose to align with either the West or the East.</div>", "topic": "NIGERIA’S FOREIGN POLICY : NIGERIA’S NON-ALIGNMENT POLICY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Before a new member is admitted to the United Nations Organization, its application must be approved by all</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">permanent members of the security council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">members of the General Assembly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">members of the economic and social council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">members of the international council of justice</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Before a new member is admitted to the United Nations Organization, its application must be approved by all permanent members of the security council. The Security Council is one of the six main organs of the UN, charged with ensuring international peace and security, accepting new members to the United Nations and approving any changes to its charter. Its powers include the establishment of peacekeeping operations, the establishment of international sanctions, and the authorization of military action through Security Council resolutions.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : UNO"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following international organizations was in existence before the outbreak of the second world war?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the OAU</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the League of Nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the UNO</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the ECOWAS</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The League of Nations was an international organization, headquartered in Geneva, Switzerland, created after the First World War to provide a forum for resolving international disputes. It was first proposed by President Woodrow Wilson as part of his Fourteen Points plan for an equitable peace in Europe, but the United States never joined the League. The league was officially dissolved on 20 April 1946, after the United Nations (UN) had been established.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : UNO"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The organ of the United Nations Organization responsible for the former colonies of defeated world war ll powers is the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">General Assembly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Security Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic and Social Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Trusteeship Council</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Trusteeship Council is one of the six main organs of the United Nations, established to ensure that trust territories were administered in the best interests of their inhabitants and of international peace and security. The trust territories—most of them former mandates of the League of Nations or territories taken from nations defeated at the end of World War II—have all now attained self-government or independence, either as separate nations or by joining neighbouring independent countries.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS : UNO"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the underlying principles of Nigerian foreign policy is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encouragement of peace - keeping operations in Africa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interference in the internal activities of other countries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">non-commitment towards African unity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> respect for sovereign equality of all states</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The underlying principles of Nigerian foreign policy include respect for the sovereignty of other nations, non-interference in the internal affairs of other countries, and commitment to African unity. The principle of respect for sovereign equality of all states means that Nigeria respects the sovereignty of other nations and does not interfere in their internal affairs. This principle is in line with the United Nations Charter which emphasizes respect for the sovereignty and territorial integrity of all nations.</div>", "topic": "NIGERIA’S FOREIGN POLICY : NIGERIA’S NON-ALIGNMENT POLICY"}, {"id": "objective>Government>1999>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principle of collective responsibility implies that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individual views cannot be expressed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">decision taken are defended inspite of individual opinions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">those who have a different views must acquiesce</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">government cannot be personalized</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The principle of collective responsibility in government implies that all members of a government are collectively responsible for the decisions and policies of the government. This means that even if an individual member of the government has a different opinion, once a decision is made by the government, all members must defend and support that decision. This principle ensures unity and consistency in government policy and action.</div>", "topic": "PRINCIPLES OF DEMOCRATIC GOVERNMENT : SEPARATION OF POWER, CHECKS AND BALANCES AND INDIVIDUAL/COLLECTIVE RESPONSIBILITY"}];
